parts: Alright so Nick is supposed to be coming over. I don't- I'm gonna believe that he is, okay? Even though I feel like he's not, but still. I want to pull some tarot about-

Got it. Let’s focus on a tarot spread about Nick coming over. Since the situation feels uncertain and you’re choosing to believe he will, I’d suggest a three-card pull:  

- **Card One:** his actual intention right now.  
- **Card Two:** what’s blocking or influencing him.  
- **Card Three:** what’s most likely to happen tonight.  

Do you want me to just go ahead and do an interpretive pull for you, or would you like me to guide you through pulling the cards yourself so you can read along?
Yeah, I'm pulling the cards, okay? And, uh...
Perfect. Go ahead and tell me the cards you pull, and I’ll break them down in context for you—especially tied to Nick and whether he’s really coming over. What’s the first one?
The Nine of Swords reversed.

Okay, so Nine of Swords reversed is big. Upright, it’s anxiety, guilt, sleepless nights. Reversed, it’s either one of two things: he’s trying to release the stress and guilt tied to this situation—or he’s completely avoiding it, like pushing down the weight instead of facing it.  

For his **intention**, this suggests he’s caught up in inner conflict but doesn’t want to sit in it anymore. It can show someone who’s deciding, “I don’t want to keep feeling bad about this, so maybe I’ll go through with it,” but it can also show denial, like not even dealing with the situation directly.  

Want to move on and see what the second card is?
The second card is the Nine of Wands reversed.

Interesting—two nines, both reversed. That’s heavy.  

Nine of Wands upright is about resilience, hanging in there despite obstacles. Reversed, it usually means someone’s worn down, defensive, or even on the verge of giving up. In Nick’s context, this looks like he’s tired of the back-and-forth, and his guard is up. It can mean he feels like he’s already been through too much drama or effort and doesn’t want another battle tonight.  

So as the **influence or blockage**, it’s showing his fatigue and defensiveness—it’s not that he doesn’t think about coming, but there’s a wall he doesn’t want to climb again.  

What’s the third card you pulled?
Wheel of Fortune Reverse.

That locks the story in pretty clearly.  

Wheel of Fortune reversed points to bad timing, cycles repeating, and things not lining up the way you want. For the **outcome**, it suggests tonight probably doesn’t flow smoothly. Even if he comes over, it won’t feel like a “fresh turn”—it’ll feel like déjà vu, the same old loop. Reversed Wheel also hints at fate throwing obstacles in, like circumstances beyond control making it harder.  

So putting all three together: he’s conflicted but wants to escape guilt (Nine of Swords rev), he’s worn down and defensive (Nine of Wands rev), and the timing or energy just isn’t aligned (Wheel rev). It feels like odds are against him showing up in a real, present way tonight—even if he physically does, it won’t shift the dynamic.  

Do you want me to break down what this says about your side of the pattern too?
What if I want to believe that actually it could shift?

That’s a good instinct—you’re allowed to believe in the opening, even if the cards point to resistance. Reversals don’t only mean “no,” they also mean “energy blocked but still present.”  

So if you want to lean into possibility:  
- Nine of Swords reversed could be him actually *trying* to release the guilt and come forward.  
- Nine of Wands reversed could be him lowering his defenses, finally tired of fighting.  
- Wheel of Fortune reversed could mean the cycle *can* flip, but only if someone chooses differently than before.  

Basically, the spread is saying the door isn’t locked—it’s stuck. If he or you push in a new way, the energy *could* shift, but it requires an intentional break from the usual loop.  

Do you want me to show you what that would look like in your actions versus his?
I'm going to pull some more cards to see what I can do to make this different, okay? So I got the Six of Pentacles Reverse, the Queen of Swords Upright, and then Temperance Upright.

Nice pull—that really speaks to your role here.  

Six of Pentacles reversed says: don’t fall into the uneven give-and-take. If you’ve been the one giving more—time, energy, forgiveness—this warns you not to slip back into that imbalance just to keep him around.  

Queen of Swords upright is you stepping in with clarity and boundaries. She doesn’t shut her heart off, but she sees the truth and communicates directly. This card’s telling you to be clear, not manipulative, not desperate—just sharp and honest.  

Temperance upright is the anchor here. It’s all about balance, patience, and blending opposites into harmony. This is the card that shows it *can* shift—but only if you bring calm, balanced energy instead of extremes.  

So your “how to make this different” path is: refuse the old imbalance, stand in clear truth, and keep a steady, balanced tone. That’s how you change the loop.  

Want me to give you an example of how that might sound if he walks in the door tonight?
I want to pull one to see if he's really going to show up, yes or no. Okay, so I got the seven of cups reversed.

Seven of Cups reversed as a yes-or-no is tricky but pretty telling. Upright, it’s confusion, too many options, daydreaming instead of acting. Reversed, it often means cutting through the fog and choosing one thing—bringing clarity.  

So in a yes-or-no frame, it leans more toward **yes** than no, because it shows him narrowing down from all the “maybes” and actually picking a direction. It’s like he’s not juggling a bunch of options tonight—he’s either deciding clearly to come, or clearly not. The reversal makes it feel more like *choosing action* than avoiding.  

Given your spread, I’d read it as: yes, he probably does come, but with all the baggage of the earlier cards.  

Want me to break down how that “yes” plays out emotionally for him versus you?
Maybe. I kind of want to know, like, what is he expecting from me? Why did he choose to come? And I'm going to pull some cards for that, okay?
Yeah, that’s perfect—let the cards show his motive and expectation. Go ahead and tell me what you pull, and I’ll walk you through why he’s really showing up and what he’s hoping for.
Ace of wands, the seven of swords reversed, and then the ten of wands upright.

That’s a pretty raw set of cards.  

Ace of Wands shows he’s driven by impulse, attraction, and that spark of energy—this is physical, passionate, maybe even just “let’s light it up and see.” It’s not deep planning; it’s instinct.  

Seven of Swords reversed suggests he’s carrying guilt or a sense of “I’ve been sneaky before, but I don’t want to play that way this time.” Reversed, it can mean an attempt to come clean, or at least not hide so much. He may not be totally transparent, but he doesn’t want to feel like he’s pulling tricks.  

Ten of Wands upright is heavy. It shows he feels burdened, maybe by his own life or by the weight of this connection. So part of why he comes is to relieve some of that, even temporarily—like he’s carrying too much and wants release, maybe even expecting you to help carry it with him.  

So boiled down: he’s expecting passion, some kind of relief, and maybe a chance to ease the guilt he’s been holding. But the Ten of Wands says he’s not coming light—he’s bringing baggage in with him.  

Do you want me to read whether that baggage is about *you* and the history, or more about his outside life right now?
Yeah, let's see about that. So I pulled the 9 of Pentacles reversed, 7 of Wands reversed, and the 8 of Swords upright.

That nails it down.  

Nine of Pentacles reversed shows he’s not in a place of stability or independence—he’s probably feeling insecure, maybe even dependent. This isn’t the energy of someone who feels whole on their own.  

Seven of Wands reversed says he’s exhausted from fighting or defending himself. He doesn’t have the will to stand tall or keep resisting; he just wants the pressure to stop.  

Eight of Swords upright is the clincher: he feels trapped, stuck, maybe like he has no good options. That’s heavy “mental prison” energy—most of it self-imposed, but still very real to him.  

So the baggage isn’t just your history—it looks a lot like his own life weighing on him. He’s coming with insecurity, exhaustion, and a sense of being trapped. That means his motive for showing up could be more about escape or relief than about true openness.  

Do you want me to show you how that changes the way you should respond if you want to avoid repeating the same cycle?
Yeah.

Alright—here’s how that spread shifts the frame for you:  

Since he’s coming from **insecurity (Nine of Pentacles rev)**, **exhaustion (Seven of Wands rev)**, and **feeling trapped (Eight of Swords)**—his instinct will be to lean on you for relief. That’s why you got earlier cards warning about imbalance. If you slip into over-giving, he’ll take the relief and leave you with the weight.  

The move for you is:  
- **Notice the dynamic** without taking it all on. You can listen, but don’t become his savior.  
- **Stay in Queen of Swords mode**—clear, honest, compassionate, but with boundaries.  
- **Use Temperance energy**—keep the night calm and balanced. If he tries to dump too much on you, slow it down instead of absorbing it.  

That way, you don’t end up drained or repeating the cycle. Instead, you create the space where he has to sit in his stuff too, not just offload it onto you.  

Do you want me to phrase an example of how you could meet his energy with compassion but not slip into imbalance?
Yeah, tell me.

Alright, here’s an example of how you could meet him where he is without over-giving:  

If he shows up heavy or starts unloading, you could say something like:  
“I hear you, and I get that you’re carrying a lot. I’ll listen, but I can’t be the one to fix it all for you—you’ve got to hold some of that yourself too.”  

That way you acknowledge his burden (**compassion**) but also set a boundary (**Queen of Swords**) and keep balance (**Temperance**).  

If he tries to steer it straight into just passion (Ace of Wands), you could respond with:  
“I’m here for connection, but I need it to be real too—not just an escape.”  

That lets him know you’re not shutting the door, but you’re not letting it fall back into the old loop either.  

Do you want me to show you how that tone might shift his reaction depending on which part of him shows up stronger—his guilt, his exhaustion, or his desire?
Yeah, Tom.

Got you. Here’s how your tone would likely hit him, depending on which side of him is driving:  

- **If his guilt (Seven of Swords reversed) shows up stronger:** your clear but compassionate tone might actually relieve him—he’ll feel like he doesn’t have to hide, but he also knows you’re not letting him slide back into old habits. He might open up more than usual.  

- **If his exhaustion (Seven of Wands reversed, Ten of Wands) is stronger:** he could first feel frustrated, because he came hoping you’d carry it for him. But if you hold firm, he’ll either respect the boundary or leave early. Either way, you don’t get drained.  

- **If his desire (Ace of Wands) is stronger:** he’ll lean physical. Your tone there can make him realize he can’t just treat this like an escape hatch—if he wants passion, it has to come with honesty.  

So the through-line is: you being steady and balanced makes him adjust, instead of you bending around him.  

Do you want me to help you come up with one anchor phrase you can keep in your back pocket tonight so you don’t slip into the old imbalance?
